";s:8:"body_p_a";s:119:"OGCsome
newssimple
profile of the GML v3.1.1 standardSharpMapGeography
Markup Language, Foundation for the Geo-WebWiley";s:9:"body_p_em";s:357:"This profile defines a restricted but useful subset of XML-Schema and GML to lower
the “implementation bar” of time and resources required for an organization to commit
for developing software that supports GML. [...] this profile facilitates the ability
to use WFS for interoperable feature data exchange with much less software development
investment.";s:5:"title";s:42:"OGC releases a "simplified" version of GML";s:4:"guid";s:80:"http://www.sharpgis.net/PermaLink,guid,66e996f8-75b4-4f47-b1e6-992215a81649.aspx";s:4:"link";s:74:"http://www.sharpgis.net/2006/06/06/OGCReleasesASimplifiedVersionOfGML.aspx";s:7:"pubdate";s:29:"Tue, 06 Jun 2006 20:04:17 GMT";s:11:"description";s:1653:"<p>
I just read this days newsletter from <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/">OGC</a>,
containing <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/press/?page=pressrelease&amp;year=0&amp;prid=260">some
news</a> on the release of a <a href="http://portal.opengeospatial.org/files/?artifact_id=15201">simple
profile of the GML v3.1.1 standard</a>. From the standard one can read the following
in the introduction:
</p>
<p>
<em>This profile defines a restricted but useful subset of XML-Schema and GML to lower
the “implementation bar” of time and resources required for an organization to commit
for developing software that supports GML. [...] this profile facilitates the ability
to use WFS for interoperable feature data exchange with much less software development
investment.</em>
</p>
<p>
The GML standard is a&nbsp;big and complex standard, and I really think this is a
great move by the OGC. This is a&nbsp;30 page long specification (well 117 if you
include the annex), and&nbsp;it's nothing compared to the 267 (601) pages full GML
spec.
</p>
<p>
Hopefully we'll see more GML support in the future. At least this finally got me started
with&nbsp;implementing GML/WFS support into <a href="http://sharpmap.iter.dk">SharpMap</a>.
</p>
<p>
Well, while I'm at it, if you want to know more on the GML specification, I can recommend
the book "<a href="http://eu.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0470871547.html">Geography
Markup Language, Foundation for the Geo-Web</a>" by Ron Lake from <a href="http://www.wiley.com">Wiley</a>.
</p>
<img width="0" height="0" src="http://www.sharpgis.net/aggbug.ashx?id=66e996f8-75b4-4f47-b1e6-992215a81649" />";s:8:"comments";s:82:"http://www.sharpgis.net/CommentView,guid,66e996f8-75b4-4f47-b1e6-992215a81649.aspx";s:8:"category";s:3:"GIS";s:7:"summary";s:1653:"<p>
I just read this days newsletter from <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/">OGC</a>,
containing <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/press/?page=pressrelease&amp;year=0&amp;prid=260">some
news</a> on the release of a <a href="http://portal.opengeospatial.org/files/?artifact_id=15201">simple
profile of the GML v3.1.1 standard</a>. From the standard one can read the following
in the introduction:
</p>
<p>
<em>This profile defines a restricted but useful subset of XML-Schema and GML to lower
the “implementation bar” of time and resources required for an organization to commit
for developing software that supports GML. [...] this profile facilitates the ability
to use WFS for interoperable feature data exchange with much less software development
investment.</em>
</p>
<p>
The GML standard is a&nbsp;big and complex standard, and I really think this is a
great move by the OGC. This is a&nbsp;30 page long specification (well 117 if you
include the annex), and&nbsp;it's nothing compared to the 267 (601) pages full GML
spec.
</p>
<p>
Hopefully we'll see more GML support in the future. At least this finally got me started
with&nbsp;implementing GML/WFS support into <a href="http://sharpmap.iter.dk">SharpMap</a>.
</p>
<p>
Well, while I'm at it, if you want to know more on the GML specification, I can recommend
the book "<a href="http://eu.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0470871547.html">Geography
Markup Language, Foundation for the Geo-Web</a>" by Ron Lake from <a href="http://www.wiley.com">Wiley</a>.
</p>
